### 1. One-Line Summary

Tenergy 80 is the easier, more explosive all-round topspin rubber with stronger built-in speed and countering ability, while H8-80 is the tackier, more deliberate spin-control rubber that rewards fuller acceleration, stronger brushing, and tighter short-game management.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown

* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Tenergy 80 is clearly livelier on compact strokes, soft counters, and backhand exchanges. It gives you speed without asking for much effort. H8-80 is slower and more subdued at low impact, so it feels more controlled but less free.
    * **Top End:** Tenergy 80 still has the higher and easier top-end pace in real match play because the spring effect is always available. H8-80 can produce strong pace when you engage hard, but it is more stroke-dependent and does not release speed as automatically.
    * **Linearity:** H8-80 is more linear and predictable from touch shots into full swings. Tenergy 80 has a more pronounced built-in kick, which is useful offensively but less neutral.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** H8-80 has the advantage on opening against backspin. The tackier topsheet and longer grab make it easier to lift heavy underspin with a thin, spin-focused contact.
    * **Max Spin:** On pure brush-based maximum rotation, H8-80 has the edge. On fast topspin in open rallies, Tenergy 80 produces very strong spin too, but with more speed mixed into the ball.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Tenergy 80 has a grippy, elastic topsheet feel. H8-80 has the more Chinese-style sticky/grabby contact, so the ball feels held longer on slow and medium brushing shots.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Tenergy 80 has a medium to medium-high arc and is lower-throwing than Tenergy 05, but it still clears the net comfortably. H8-80 usually produces a more spin-shaped, lifting arc on opening loops, especially against backspin.
    * **Safety:** H8-80 feels safer when you are opening carefully or playing heavy first-ball spin. Tenergy 80 feels safer when the rally becomes fast and you need easy pace, quick recovery, and topspin-to-topspin stability.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Tenergy 80 feels crisp, elastic, and springy. H8-80 feels denser, grabbier, and more connected to the ball, with a more traditional Chinese-hybrid character.
    * **Dwell:** H8-80 gives the clearer sense of dwell on brush loops and touch play. Tenergy 80 holds the ball well for a tension rubber, but the release is quicker and more dynamic.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Tenergy 80 is more reactive to incoming spin and touch errors because of its built-in tension and rebound. H8-80 is less bouncy in the short game, so it is easier to keep pushes, drop shots, and receive quality low.
    * **Touch Play:** H8-80 is better for short pushes, loaded receives, and deliberate placement. Tenergy 80 is more likely to pop the ball up if your touch is not precise enough.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** H8-80 is steadier and easier to deaden on passive blocks. Tenergy 80 blocks well too, but the rebound is more active, so the angle control must be cleaner.
    * **Active Counter:** Tenergy 80 is the better rubber for fast active counters, punchy backhand exchanges, and quick timing over the table. H8-80 can counter well when you engage properly, but it is less effortless and less explosive.

### 3. The Recommendation

* **Choose Tenergy 80 if:**
    * You want easier speed, easier counterattack, and better performance in fast topspin rallies.
    * You play an all-round offensive game and want one rubber that works well for looping, blocking, and countering without much adjustment.
    * You prefer a modern Japanese tension feel with more automatic pace and less need to supply everything yourself.
    * You want the safer choice for backhand or for two-winged topspin play.

* **Choose H8-80 if:**
    * You value opening spin, short-game control, and a tackier contact more than free speed.
    * You like a more linear Chinese-style response but want something easier and more elastic than a classic hard Hurricane setup.
    * You are willing to generate speed with your own acceleration in exchange for better touch, heavier first-ball spin, and calmer receive play.
    * You want a rubber that can work especially well on forehand for spin-first attackers, or on backhand for players who like tacky control and a more held ball.
